A DRIVER OF A 1991 TOYOTA 4 X4 WITH MARYLAND LICENSE PLATE 1BK-735 ENTERED SERVICE STATION, RAN OVER AT LEAST ONE CONE AND THEN HIT AND BROKE DELIVERY FITTING. BRUNSON IMMEDIATELY CLOSED VALVE TO THAT FITTING, HOWEVER BROKEN FITTING ALLOWED LESS THAN 40 GALLONS TO SPILL.  FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (CASE# 101619).  MARYLAND NATURAL RESOURCES WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

column168: DURING THE MORNING WORK HOURS, WORKERS NOTICED FUMES EMANATING FROM INBOUND TRAILER P1372.  WHEN THE TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED.  THEY FOUND ONE DRUM OF RESIN LEAKING AT THE TOP.
CRACK IN TANK SHELL UNER JACKET, "B" END.  CONTENTS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK TRUCKS.

WHEN DOCKMAN TILTED DRUMS BACK ON DRUM CART TO UNLOAD, CONTENTS BEGAN TO LEAK FROM TOP DRUM HEAD SEAL.  INSPECTION OF THE DRUMS REVEALED THAT GASKETS USED IN THE DRUM HEAD WERE THE WRONG SINGE (GASKET WERE FOR 85 GAL. DRUM) PREVENTING A PROPER SEEL FROM BEING ACCOMPLISHED.  NEW GASKETS WERE R\FROMED WIHT SHRINK WRAP AND THE DRUMS WERE RESEALED,

PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF ONE OF THE EARS, BY THE TANK, ON A DOUBLE 2" FEMALE CONNECTION WHEN HE STARTED UNLOADING PRODUCT MISSED THE BUCKET BECAUSE IT IS A REAR UNLOAD AND PRODUCT HIT THE BUMPER.  DRIVER CLEANED UP.

DURING SWITCHING, VAPOR WAS NOTICED COMING FROM TOP OF CAR.  SMALL AMOUNT OF DISCOLORATION INDICATRED A SMALL LIQUID SPLASH HAD OCCURRED.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC AND THEY REPLACED RUPTURED DISC.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHEN RUPTURE DISC FAILED.

BIRCH RUN DOCKMAN WENT TO TOPLOAD THIS GROUP OF 4 DRUMS ALREADY PLATFORMED ON DOCK WITH A LIGHT PALLET TO MISCELLANEOUS FREIGHT IN ORDER TO CONSERVE DOCK SPACE.  AS HE LOWERED THE PALLET ONTO THE DRUMS, THE CYLINDER IN BETWEEN THE FORKLIFT MASTS STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE SLIGHTLY PROTRUDING FIRST RING ON THE DRUM RESULTING ON THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF DENATURED ALCOHOL WHICH QUICKLY EVAPORATED.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE ON A PALLET & THE HOLE WAS COVERED & TAPED TO PREVENT FURTHER EVAPORATION.  SECURED AUTHORIZATION TO RETURN DRUM TO SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION AND CREDIT.

column168: ONE PALLET OF FOUR, 15 GALLON DRUMS SET ON TOP OF ANOTHER PALLET ON REAR TRAILER.  NO DUNNAGE AHEAD OF TOP PALLET WHICH SLID FORWARD INTO AN EMPTY SPACE AND ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY BOTTOM OF ANOTHER WOOD PALLET AHEAD OF DRUM, A SMALL PUNCTURE.  LESS THAN 1/2 CUP SEEPED OUT THE PUNCTURE AND WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD OF THE FIBER DRUM PACKED IN.  DRUM WAS PUT INSIDE AN 85 GALLON ABF RECOVERY DRUM INSIDE PLASTIC LINER AND PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  HAVE NOTIFIED ORIGIN TERMINAL TO CONTACT SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.  LOADING TERMINAL WILL BE INSTRUCTED IN PROPER LOADING.

SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON SKID AND DRUM FELL OFF SKID ONTO 2-WHEELER HANDLE CAUSING PUNCTURE IN DRUM.  PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY CONSIGNEE.  DRUM WAS RECOOPED AND RETURNED TO TERMINAL.  AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER. PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING WILL BE ADRESSED WITH CITY DRIVER.
PRODUCT WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT DURING LOADING.  IT WAS THEN RECOOPED INTO A RECOVERY PAIL, MARKED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  ADDITIONAL LOADING INSTRUCTIONS WILL BE GIVEN TO OPERATOR.
1. VAPOR VALVE SLIGHTLY OPEN - PLUG HAND TIGHT. 2. CLOSED VALVE TIGHTENED PLUG WRENCH TIGHT.

WHEN UNLOADING LAST PALLET AT RECEIVER, THERE WAS A PUNCTURE FOUND IN ONE OF THE BAGS APPARENTLY FROM A FORKLIFT SINCE THE DAMAGE WAS TO THE INNER PART OF THE PALLET - AWAY FROM THE WALL.  THE MATERIAL WAS SWEPT OUT OF TRAILER & DISPOSED OF BY THE RECEIVER.  TRAILER WAS ALSO WASHED OUT BY THE RECEIVER FOLLOWING THE M.S.D.S. GUIDELINES.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS DRIVING INTO DELIVERY VAN TO UNLOAD PRODUCT.  THE VAN WAS SITTING AT AN ANGLE BECAUSE OF THE DOCK ALIGNMENT.  THE FORKLIFT SLID ON THE VAN FLOOR AND THE TINES PUNCTURED TWO STEEL DRUMS.  PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED AND MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO NEW DRUMS.  APPLY NON-SKID MATERIAL TO FLOOR OF TRUCK WHEN APPLICABLE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY VEHICLE TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAVING ROADWAY ON ROUTE #22 THREE (3) MILES EAST OF HUNTINGDON, PA.  THE VEHICLE TRAVELED DOWN A TWENTY (20) FOOT ENBANKMENT AND CAME TO REST ON CONRAIL RIGHT-OF-WAY, CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS CALLED AND CONDUCTED BY ELDRIDGE, INC. AND SUPERVISED BY THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES.  THE ACCIDENT WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED OF ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES AND CONRAIL.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE FREIGHT, THE LEAKING CARTON WAS DISCOVERED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  IT APPEARED THAT THE CARTON HAD EITHER FALLEN OR BEEN DROPPED.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TWO (2) OF THE FOUR (4) GLASS BOTTLES WITHIN THE CARTON WERE SHATTERED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP, CONTAINED IN TWO (2) RECOVERY DRUMS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR INSPECTION AND DISPOSITION.  IT IS SUGGESTED THAT BETTER MATERIAL COULD BE USED WITHIN THE CARTON TO PROTECT THE GLASS BOTTLES.
A CARTON OF CORROSIVE LIQUID MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM CAP AREA DUE TO BEING LOADED UPSIDE DOWN.  FREIGHT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.  MINIMAL PRODUCT LOSS.
WHEN WE FOUND THE BARREL, IT WAS LEAKING OUT THE TOP INTO THE TRAILER.
A CORROSIVE DRUM WHEN TURNED TO MOVE HAD LIQUID SPLASH FROM THE SEAL AREA. MINIMAL LEAKAGE.  DRUM WAS RESEALED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. DELIVERED CLEAR.

A CARTON OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID HAD 2 PAILS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE. MINIMAL LEAKAGE FROM CUTS IN PAIL.  MATERIAL RECOUPERED INTO NEW PAILS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CREDIT AND INSPECTION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1138 HOURS, TUESDAY, JANUARY 7, 1991, DOT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR E. RUDOLPH REPORTED TO CONRAIL TRAINMASTER/GENERAL CAR FOREMAN D. SHEPPARD THAT HE HAD FOUND A SLIGHT LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP OF TANK CAR ECUX-374023 (PETROLEUM NAPTHA).  CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE MGA RAILROAD INTERCHANGE TRACK AT THE CONRAIL W. BROWNSVILLE RAIL YARD IN W. BROWNSVILLE, PENNSYLVANIA. TANK CAR WAS REINSPECTED BY TRAINMASTER/GENERAL CAR FOREMAN SHEPPARD AND ROAD FOREMAN W. KUNZ.  NO EVIDENCE COULD BE FOUND OF THE CAR LEAKING DURING REINSPECTION.  ADDITIONALLY, CAR HAD BEEN IN SAME LOCATION SINCE 0630 HOURS, 01/07/92 AND NO LIQUID PRODUCT WAS DETECTED ON THE GROUND IMMEDIATELY BELOW THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  INSPECTION WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 1250 HOURS, 01/07/92 AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION.

AT APROXIMATELY 1745 HOURS, THURSDAY, JANUARY 9, 1992, COT/FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTOR J. CONNELLY DISCOVERED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR ACFX-88424 (SODIUM HYDROXIDE, LIQUID) WHILE CONDUCTING INSPECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TANK CARS AT THE CONRAIL BUCKEYE RAIL YARD IN COLUMBUS, OH.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. TANK CAR WAS INSPECTED BY CONRAIL CAR FOREMAN G.A. ZEBIN WHO, UPON EXAMINATION, DISCOVERED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE CAR'S SAFETY VENT HAD RUPTURED, ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A COMPATIBLE 100 POUND FRANGIBLE DISK. CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1820 HOURS, JANUARY 9, 1992.

WHEN THE DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY HE ROLLED UP THE HOSE AND WHEN HE STARTED TO GET IN TO HIS TRUCK THE DELIVERY HOSE BURST LEAKING ABOUT 7 GALLONS OF OIL ONTO THE DRIVEWAY.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DEFECTIVE PART REPLACED.

DAMAGED PARCEL WAS REPACKED BY HUB SHIFT.  PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING IN BIN ON FAIR OAKS BOXLINE.  ONE GALLON CONTAINER HAD CRACKED ALONG SEAM AND WAS REWRAPPED IN PLASTIC BAG, SURROUNDED WITH PAPER AND REBOXED TO BE DELIVERED.  THERE WERE NO EXTERNAL MARKINGS ON PACKAGE TO INDICATE IT AS A DOT CONTROLLED MATERIAL.  COMPLETE ORDER HAD TO BE SCRAPPED.  THE DAMAGED PACKING MATERIAL AND CARTON WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING CURRENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE GAUGING OF THE TANK.  CONSIGNEE ADVISED THAT LOAD WOULD HOLD.  AS DELIVERY WAS BEING COMPLETED, TANK OVERFILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS BEING SPILLED.  ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A DIKED AREA.

AFTER DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY AND HE WAS REWINDING HIS DELIVERY HOSE THE REWIND BUTTON STUCK.  THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE HOSE AND THE NOZZLE CAME OPEN SPILLING ABOUT 10-14 GALLONS OF OIL.  OIL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE SWITCH WAS REPLACED.

WHEN OUR DRIVER WENT TO TILT THE BARREL BACK TO PUT ON THE HAND TRUCK THERE WAS SOME RESIDUE OF THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL ON TOP AND IT SPLASHED ON OUR DRIVERS ARM.  THE DRIVER DIDN'T NOTICE IT UNTIL IT STARTED TO IRRITTE THE SKIN.  HE WENT TO RINSE IF OFF HIS SKID AND IT LEFT RED MARKS, SO AS A PRECAUTION WE SENT HIM DOWN TO THE CLINIC TO GET IF CHECKED OUT.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED AND NO FURTHER MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NECESSARY.  THE CLEANUP WAS HANDLED AT THE SHIPPER BY SODA ASH AND THE SHIPMENT WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO THE CONSIGNEE.
DRIVER OVERFILLED TANK AND OIL DISCHARGED FROM VENT PIPE. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLON OF #2 HEATING OIL WAS SPILLED AND CLEANED UP.
CUSTOMER HAD A BRAND NEW LINE AND THE FITTING WASN'T TIGHT ON THEIR VALVE AND PRODUCT LEAKED OUT. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP.
AIR ELIMINATOR BLEW OUT ABOUT 3 TEASPOONS OF PRODUCT WHEN FINISHED UNLOADING. CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBANT PADS.

column168: SUPERIOR DRIVER ARRIVED AT RHONE POULENC, COLUMBIA, SC TO UNLOAD A LOAD OF CAUSTIC SODA. HE HOOKED UP HIS UNLOADING LINES AND STARTED TO UNLOAD. HE NOTICED A SMALL LEAK AT THE CUSTOMER HOOK UP. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN ALL VALVES NOTIFIED PLANT PERSONNEL WHO NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR REQUESTED THE DRIVER TO UNHOOK UNLOADING LINE CAUSING APPROX 2 TO 3 GALLON SPILL. I HAD PREVIOUSLY INSTRUCTED MY DRIVER TO SHIM THE QUICK COUPLING AND REQUEST A BUCKET. AFTER RECONNECTION OF UNLOADING LINE AND APPROX 40 MIN OF UNLOADING UNDER AIR PRESSURE 3 INCHES OF PRODUCT WAS IN A 5 GAL BUCKET. THE AREA WAS COMPLETELY WASHED DOWN WITH WATER. SUPERIOR CARRIERS HAS REQUESTED THAT THE UNLOADING VALVE (CUSTOMERS) BE LOWERED FROM EYE LEVEL TO BELOW WAIST LEVEL FOR SAFETY.

column168: SECTION VI-ITEM 13: K071-BRINE PURIFICATION MUDS FROM THE MERCURY CELL PROCESS IN CHLORINE PRODUCTION WHERE SEPARATELY PRE-PURIFIED BRINE IN NOT USED. K106-WASTE WATER TREATMENT SLUDGE FROM THE MERCURY CELL PROCESS IN CHLORINE PRODUCTION. IX. DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS: A DUMP TRAILER CONTAINING K071/5106 WASTE WAS ENROUTE TO STABLEX, LOCATED IN QUEBEC, CANADA FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE BRAINTREE, MA  02184 ON JANUARY 22, 1991.  UPON EXIT FROM THE CLEAN HARBORS FACILITY, THE LOAD WAS CHECKED AN NO FREE LIQUIDS WERE PRESENT.  ON THE MORNING OF 1/23/92, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND NOTICED 2 DRIPS COMING FROM THE TAILGATE OF THIS VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PLACED 5 GALLON PAILS UNDER THE TAILGATE TO COLLECT ANY PRODUCT THAT ESCAPED FROM THE VEHICLE.  HE THEN CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED BOTH THE STATE OF VERMONT AND THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER.  THE RESPONSE CENTER ISSUED THE ABOVE MENTIONED INCIDENT REPORT #104223.  AFTER THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER, HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THE MANAGEMENT OF THE WAGON WHEEL TRUCK STOP AT EXIT 19 ON I-89 OF THE INCIDENT.  THE MANAGEMENT OF THE TRUCK STOP ASKED THAT THEY BE KEPT INFORMED OF THE PROGRESS OF THE CLEAN-UP.  A CREW OF RESPONDERS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED FROM THE CLEAN HARBORS, ALBANY, NY SERVICE CENTER.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE CREW FROM ALBANY, THEY PLACED ADDITIONAL POLY SHEETING UNDER THE VEHICLE AND INSPECTED THE LOAD. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IN TRANSIT, RESIDUAL LIQUIDS HAD SEPARATED FROM THE LOAD.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE SHOVELED INTO THE DUMP TRAILER NEAR THE REAR TAILGATE AREA.  A CAULKING COMPOUND WAS ALSO APPLIED TO THE SEAL OF THE DOOR AS AN ADDED MEASURE OF PROTECTION.  THIS, HOWEVER, DID NOT EFFECTIVELY SEAL THE REAR TAILGATE.  THE CREW THEN PROCEEDED TO SHOVEL THE MATERIAL AWAY FROM THE TAILGATE AND ADDED A CEMENT COMPOUND THAT WHEN MIXED WITH THE LOAD SIGNIFICANTLY REDUCED THE LIQUID CONTENT IN THE TRAILER.  ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS ALSO ADDED TO THE LOAD TO ABSORB ANY REMAINING MOISTURE.  THE LOAD WAS THEN OBSERVED AND WAS FOUND TO HAVE STOPPED LEAKING.  ALL THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL THAT WAS USED DURING THE RESPONSE WAS ADDED TO THE LOAD AND THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED ON ITS WAY TO THE ORIGINAL DESTINATION. STEPS THAT HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO INSURE THAT THIS SITUATION DOES NOT REOCCUR INCLUDE: 1) INSPECTION OF MATERIAL PRIOR TO LOADING TO INSURE THAT THERE IS NO LIQUID CONTENT THAT COULD SEPARATE DURING TRANSPORTATION. 2) INSPECTION OF ALL GASKETS TO INSURE A PROPER SEAL. 3) ADDITION OF A LAYER OF SPEEDI DRY OR OTHER SUITABLE ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED AS AN ADDED MEASURE OF PROTECTION TO ABSORB ANY RESIDUAL LIQUIDS THAT DO SEPARATE DURING TRANSIT.

column42: PHOSPHORUS PENTASULFIDE, FREE FROM YELLOW OR WHITE PHOSPHORUS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2030 HOURS, JANUARY 19, 1991, CREW OF CONRAIL TRAIN INCO-9X OBSERVED A FIRE ON THE FIRST CAR IN THEIR TRAIN.  TRAIN WAS TRAVELLING EAST ON THE CONRAIL INDIANAPOLIS LINE IN FORTVILE, INDIANA WHEN THE FIRE WAS FIRST OBSERVED.  CAR INVOLVED WAS A COVERED HOPPER (UTLX 80245) CONTAINING PHOSPHOROUS PENTASYULFIDE, A FLAMMABLE SOLID THAT IS WATER REACTIVE.  AT ABOUT THE SAME TIME THAT THE TRAIN OBSERVED THE FIRE, PERSONNEL FROM THE OAKLANDON FIRE DEPARTMENT WHOSE FIRE HOUSE IS ADJACENT TO THE TRACKS, SPOTTED THE FIRE ON THE COVERED HOPPER AND NOTIFIED THE CONRAIL MOVEMENT OFFICE AND ALSO DISPATCHED FIRE APPARATUS.  TRAIN CREW STOPPED THE TRAIN WITH THE COVERED HOPPER STOPPING ADJACENT TO THE 6400 BLOCK OF OAKLANDON ROAD. FIRE HAD EXTINGUISED ITSELF BY THE TIME FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND UPON INSPECTION BY FIRE AND CONRAIL OFFICIALS, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT RESIDUE HAD COLLECTED AROUND THE LOADING HATCHES DURING THE LOADING PROCESS AND HAD MIXED WITH MELTING SNOW THAT ALSO HAD ACCUMULATED ON THE CAR.  PRODUCT RESIDUE AND WATER HAD MIXED TOGETHER CAUSING A REACTION WHICH CAUSED THE FLARE UP ON THE SIDE OF THE COVERED HOPPER.  CAR WAS SET OUT OF TRAIN AND REINSPECTED BY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE MONSANTO COMPANY WHO ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS.  MONSANTO VERIFIED THAT THERE WAS NO ACTUAL LEAK OF PRODUCT AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, 01/19/92. (02/13/92)

column168: DRIVER REVERSED THE LOAD FROM CUSTOMER REQUEST.  DRIVER WAS TO LOAD 2500 GALS OF RUBY RED DIESEL FUEL AND 4600 GALS OF #2 FUEL OIL.  INSTEAD THE DRIVER LOADED 2500 GALS #2 FUEL OIL AND 4600 GALS RUBY RED DIESEL FUEL. WHEN DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE RUBY RED DIESEL FUEL THE TANK RAN OVER FROM BEING OVERFILLED.  ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE DIKE AREA AROUND THE BULK PLANT.  BECAUSE OF THE FROST LEVEL BEING IN THE GROUND THE SPILLED FUEL OIL DID NOT RUN ANYWHERE OR DID NOT GO DOWN INTO THE SOIL.  THE SPILLED FUEL OIL SATURATED THE SOIL APPROX. 3-4 INCHES DOWN.  ALL STANDING FUEL OIL WAS RECOVERED AND SOIL WAS REMOVED.  SOIL WAS REMOVED 4-5 INCHES DOWN IN ENTIRE DIKE AREA.  TESTS ARE BEING RAN ON SOIL AND DISPOSAL WILL FOLLOW NEBRASKA GUIDELINES.  TOTAL GALS SPILLED ARE ESTIMATED TO 1078 GALS.

WHILE UNLOADING INBOUND TRAILER #39015 FROM WHITE CREEKS, TN. UNLOADER NOTICED IRRITATING FUMES NEAR MIDLE OF TRAILER.  UNLOADER NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR, WHO HAD UNLOADER GET OUT OF TRAILER. SERVICE CENTER PERSONNEL RESPONDED WITH HUB SPILL CART AND PROTECTIVE CLOTHING.  THE LEAKING PACKAGE, NOT MARKED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, WAS FOUND NEAR NOSE OF TRAILER.  PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON IT'S SIDE, HALFWAY UP IN TIER WALL. THE LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SATURATED MANY CARTONS IN THE TIER.  ALL PACKAGES THAT CAME IN CONTACT WITH ACID WERE REMOVED TO HUB PSC FOR PROCESSING.  AND CORRUGATION OR MERCHANDISE THAT HAD ACID ON IT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH A WATER/BAKING SODA SOLUTION AND DOUBLE CHECKED WITH PH LITMUS PAPER. MAINTENANCE NOTIFIED WHICH CONTAINER HAD THE NEUTRALIZED REFUSE.  THE ORIGINAL BOTTLE AND CARTON BEING HELD BY DESTINATION HUB CUSTOMER SERVICE UNTIL SHIPPER IS NOTIFIED OF THIS SERIOUS INCIDENT.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED 1-14-92 AND ORIGINAL BOTTLE AND ORGINAL CARTON BEING RETURNED TO SHIPPER VIA UPS CUSTOMER SERVICE ACCOUNT EXECUTIVE IN FLORENCE, ALABAMA.
PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE.  HUB MANAGER SHOULD PERFORM MORE PACKAGE HANDLING AUDITS.

PACKAGE CAR RAN OVER PARCEL CAUSING DAMAGE.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.  HUB MANAGER SHOULD PERFORM AUDITS ON PERSONNEL WHO MOVE PACKAGE CAR INSIDE HUB BUILDING.

THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE OUTBOUNDS AREA OF SORT (PD 7). ONE OF THE 4 - 1 GALLON CANS WAS OFF.  NONE OF THE CANS HAD CLIPS ON THE LIDS.  THERE WERE NO FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABELS APPLIED TO EXTERNAL PACKAGING NOR A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL 5 PART SHIPPING LABEL.  THE DAMAGED CARTON AND EMPTY CAN WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.
PKG LEFT IN PSC AREA.  OPENED BOX TO FIND 6 CANS W/O DIVIDERS OR CUSHIONING IN BOX.  ONLY SLIGHTLY WET ON BOTTOM, OVERBOXED ENTIRE BOX AND SENT RTS DAMAGED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 11:50 AM, JANUARY 29, 1992, A CSXT 140251, BOXCAR, LOAD WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AN UNKNOWN COMMODITY WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID PLACARDS.  CAR DOOR WAS OPEN AND A CONDITION OF DAMAGED 55 GAL STEEL DRUMS WAS DISCOVERED WITH THE REASON FOR THE DAMAGE BEING THAT THE CAR WAS IMPROPERLY LOADED AND BRACED. THE SHIPPER, SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL CORP. WAS CONTACTED CONCERNING THE ABOVE AND CAR SEGREGATED TO AN ISOLATED AREA FOR REMEDIATION WORK.  SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL WITH ILL. STATE EPA ASSISTANCE UNLOADED THE CAR IN QUESTION ADN PLACED 150 DRUMS IN OVERPACK FOR SAFE TRANSPORTATION AND MOVED THE PRODUCTS IN QUESTION TO A HAZARDOUS WASTE FACILITY IN KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI FOR PROPER DISPOSAL WITH APPROVAL FROM ILLINOIS EPA. THE RAIL CAR IN QUESTION WAS DECONTAMINATED OF ANY PRODUCT RESIDUE AND UPON REQUEST OF RAIL CAR OWNER FORWARDED TO THEIR SHOP FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  ALL SOLID WASTE PRODUCTS FROM CLEAN UP RECOVERED BY SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL AND DISPOSED OF IN A PROPER FACILITY.
DRIVER INADVERTENTLY HOOKED UP TO WRONG LINE CAUSING PRODUCT TO DSICHARGE OUT OF SYSTEM.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  ALL NECESSARY REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.
AFTER UNLOADING, COMPARTMENTS WERE DRAINED INTO A BUCKET.  BUCKET WAS INADVERTENTLY KNOCKED OVER ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

AFTER DRIVER FINISHED LOADING FROM CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK INTO COMPARTMENT #2 OF OUT CARGO TANK, DRIVER DISCONNECTED SHIPPERS LOADING ARM AND TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED. THE RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF A MALFUNCTION OF THE SHIPPER'S DRY DISCONNECT FITTING. ALL PRODUCT WAS RETAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMER PERSONNEL.

APPARENTLY THE GATE VALVE IN THE MANIFOLD HAD SOMETHING LODGED UNDERNEATH BECAUSE DRIVER STATED HE HAD DOUBLE CHECKED VALVE AND IT FELT CLOSED.  THE PREMIUM NO LEAD HAD SEEPED BY THE GATE VALVE AND FORCED INTERNAL VALVE OPEN AND WENT INTO COMPARTMENT #3 AND MIXED WITH #1 DIESEL.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCE WAS SPILLED AND WAS RECOVERED IN MONTANA REFINING'S SLOP TANK.  AFTER PUMPING OFF PRODUCT THE GATE VALVE WAS CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE FUNCTIONING PROPERLY.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON JANUARY 17, 1991, GOETZ ENERGY'S UNIT NO. 101, A TANK TRAILER WAS PARKED ON COMPANY PROPERTY IN THE TERMINAL YARD LOADED WITH 7,500 GALLONS OF STOVE OIL.  AT 11:30PM A TRUCK OPERATOR, EMPLOYEE, KEN GROSSE, NOTIFIED DAVID WALSH, GENERAL MANAGER THAT HE HAD RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL TO CHANGE UNITS AND FOUND UNIT 101 COMPLETELY TURNED OVER AND RESTING ON THE TOP TANK RAILS.  MR. WALSH ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL AT APPROXIMATELY 12:10AM AND VERIFIED THE REPORT.  THE INCIDENT WAS THEN REPORTED TO THE EPA WASHINGTON HOTLINE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OFF UNIT 101 ONTO ANOTHER TANK TRAILER BY REMOVING THE EMERGENCY VALVES FROM THE TRAILER.  WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.  WHEN THE UNIT WAS TURNED OVER, THE RIGHT LEG ON THE LANDING GEAR WAS IN THE UP POSITION WITH BEND MARKS ON THE LEG SUPPORTS; THE LEFT LEG WAS STILL EXTENDED.  IT CANNOT BE DETERMINED WHETHER THE RIGHT LEG FOR SOME REASON COLLAPSED OR THE TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER VEHICLE CAUSING IT TO ROLL OVER.  THE TERMINAL IS LOCATED IN AN INDUSTRIAL AREA AND THE YARD AREA IS LIGHTED, HOWEVER, THERE DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE ANY EYE WITNESS TO THE INCIDENT.  ATTACHED ARE PHOTOGRAPHS.  UNIT WAS IN YARD AREA AND LOADED FOR APPROXIMATELY 20 HOURS PRIOR TO INCIDENT. **NO PHOTOS ATTACHED**

column168: OUR DRIVER HAD LOADED AND WAS ENROUTE TO A SCALE FOR A GROSS WEIGHT.  HE HAD TO STOP ABRUPTLY AT AN INTERSECTION AND HEARD A BANG AND THEN A SPLASH.  HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND TURNED ON HIS 4 WAY FLASHERS.  HE USED A PHONE ON THE CORNER TO CALL HIS TERMINAL AND REQUEST HELP AS WELL AS NOTIFY THE AUTHORITIES.  OUR PERSONNEL AS WELL AS THE FIRE AND ENVIRONMENTAL REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND TOOK CAR OF CLEANING UP THE SPILL AREA.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE FRONT CLEAN OUT CAP WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY AND THE SURGE OF PRODUCT DISLODGED IT.

DRIVER PERFORMED TANK MEASUREMENT (USING A TANK STICK) UPON ARRIVAL. MEASUREMENTS SHOWED THAT ALL PRODUCT WOULD FIT INTO TANK. UNBEKNOWST TO DRIVER OR PETROLEUM TRADERS' PERSONNEL, THE TANK HAD AN AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF DEVICE DESIGNED TO PREVENT OVER FILLING THE TANK.  WHEN THE PRODUCT REACHED APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS FROM THE TANK CAPACITY, THE DEVICE KICKED IN NOT ALLOWING THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT TO ENTER THE TANK. THE RESULT WAS SPILLAGE OF THE PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE DELIVERY HOSE (APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS).

DRIVERS DEPARTED SARNIA, ONTARIO, CANADA AT 17:00 HOURS ON 1/8/92 WITH A TRAILER PRESSURE OF 6 PSIG.  THROUGHOUT THE TRIP, DRIVERS EXPERIENCED NOTHING OTHER THAN NORMAL CONDITIONS UNTIL THEY STOPPED AT SCALE AT MT. AIRY, MARYLAND AT 07:00 ON 1/9/92 AND THE TRAILER PRESSURE READING WAS 11 PSIG.  AT WHITE MARSH, MARYLAND, THE DRIVER CHECKED THE UNIT AGAIN AND THE PRESSURE HAD CLIMBED AT 28 PSIG CAUSING PRODUCT TO VENT.  THE DRIVERS ADVISED THEIR DISPATCH AT THIS TIME AND WERE ADVISED TO PROCEED TO AIR PRODUCTS AND CHEMICALS, SPARROW POINT, MARYLAND PLANT TO STABILIZE THEIR TRAILER.  THEY ACCOMPLISHED THIS AND PROCEEDED ON TO DELAWARE CITY, DELAWARE WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.  THE ABNORMAL PRESSURE RISE CAN ONLY BE ATTRIBUTED TO DRIVERS'S FAILURE TO PROPERLY STABILIZE THE LOAD AT SARNIA, ONTARIO BEFORE DEPARTING.  ON SUBSEQUENT TRIPS THIS TRAILER HAS EXPERIENCED NO ABNORMAL PRESSURE CONDITIONS.

IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT THEY HAD BEEN OVERCOME BY CARBON MONOXIDE WHILE IDLING THEIR CAR MAINTAINING SECURITY ON THE STREET 700 FEET AWAY FROM THE CONTAMINATION ZONE. CARGO TANK DID NOT FAIL.  INTAKE OF TRACTOR MOUNTED PUMP WAS HOOKED (BY HOSE) TO SHIPPERS BULK STORAGE TANK. OUTLET OF PUMP WAS HOOKED TO COMPARTMENT OF CARGO TANK (CONNECTED WITH HOSE).  WHEN THE PUMP WAS STARTED, A FITTING ON THE HOSE (WHERE IT WAS CONNECTED TO THE CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT) BROKE.  THE HOSE FELL TO THE GROUND AND DISCHARGED THE SHIPPER TANK CONTENTS ONTO THE GROUND AND DISCHARGED THE SHIPPERS TANK CONTENTS ONTO THE GROUND UNTIL THE DRIVER AND ATTENDANT TURNED OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSED THE SHIPPERS TANK VALVE AND THE CARGO TANK COMPARTMENT EMERGENCY AND LINE VALVES.  CONTAINMENT OF SPILLED MATERIAL WAS COMPLETE, TESTED AND REPLACED ALL WORN HOSE FITTINGS.  ALL CONTAMINATED GRAVEL, DIRT AND WATER (ABOUT 2,000 POUNDS) COLLECTED AND AWAITING DISPOSAL EVALUATION.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT SAFEWAY. CHECKED WITH PERSONNEL FOR UNLOADING. HOOKED UP AND UNLOADED THE LOAD.  AFTER LOAD WAS FINISHED AND HOSE AND PRODUCT LINES WERE BLOWN FREE OF PRODUCT, DRIVER LET AIR OFF TANK AND UNHOOKED PRODUCT HOSE TO PUT IT AWAY.  WHILE PUTTING HOSE AWAY, PRODUCT STARTED COMING OUT OF THE UNLOADING PIPE OF CUSTOMERS TANK.  DRIVER QUICKLY RECONNECTED HOSE TO STOP RELEASE OF MATERIAL.  CUSTOMERS TANK WAS THEN DRAINED AND TANK WAS REPRESSURIZED AND LINE WAS BLOWN FREE FOR A 2ND TIME.  UPON INSPECTION OF CUSTOMERS FACILITY AFTER THE INCIDENT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT VENT PIPE FOR OVERFLOW WAS ABOVE THE LEVEL OF THE PRODUCT FILL LINE.  THIS WAS BROUGHT TO THE CUSTOMERS ATTENTION. IN ADDITION IT IS ALSO LIKELY THAT THE CHECK VALVE WITHIN THE FILL LINE WAS STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION THUS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FLOW BACK DOWN THE PIPE.  THE RELEASE OF MATERIAL WAS ABOUT 40 GALLONS AND WAS CLEANED UP BY CUSTOMERS PERSONNEL.

SECTION NO. 4 PREINCIDENT MR. LODATI AWOKE AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM. AND UPON CHECKING DISCOVERED THAT THE EXTERIOR OF TRAILER T-101 SEEMED TO BE WARMER THAN NORMAL.  THE MORNING WEATHER OF JANUARY 29, 1992 AT ELLISVILLE, FLORIDA AT THIS TIME WAS ONE OF A HEAVY FOG SO SUN LIGHT WAS NOT AFFECTING TRAILER TEMPERATURE. MR. LODATI THEN CONTACTED MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. AT 10:35 AM. TO INFORM THEM OF THE CHANGE IN THE TRAILERS TEMPERATURE.  AT THIS TIME THERE WAS NO APPARENT PRESSURE BUILDUP IN THE TRAILER AND IT'S TEMPERATURE ALLOWED ONE TO PLACE THEIR HAND ON THE SIDE FOR A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME. MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED MR. SPEER MABRY AT FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WITH ALL THE INFORMATION CONCERNING TRAILER CONDITIONS SINCE DEPARTING THE GENERATORS SITE IN MIAMI, FLORIDA TO IT'S PRESENT CONDITION. MR. MABRY SUSPECTED THAT THE REOCCURENCE OF THE HEAT MAY HAVE BEEN FROM SOME POOLED CAUSTIC REACTING WITH THE ACID IN THE TANKER, THAT THE HEAT WOULD DISSIPATE AFTER THE RECTION ENDED AND REQUESTED THAT THE DRIVER CONTINUE TO OBSERVE AND REPORT ANY CHANGES IN THE TRAILERS CONDITION. MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. THEN NOTIFIED MR. DAN MATIVI, THE DRIVER OF THE SECOND TRAILER LOADED TO EASTERN AIRLINES TO STOP AT THE LOCATION OF THE MR. LODATI'S TRAILER TO ASSIST HIM AS REQUIRED. MR. MATIVI ARRIVED ON SITE AROUND 11:45 AM, AND AFTER SPEAKING WITH MR. LODATI CONTACTED THE OFFICE.  HE INFORMED MEROLA THAT THE TRAILER APPEARED TO BE GETTING HOTTER AND REQUESTED INSTRUCTIONS AND WAS REQUESTED TO CALL BACK WITHIN SEVERAL MINUTES.  MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. AGAIN CONTACTED MR. MABRY TO INFORM HIM OF THE CURRENT STATUS OF THE TRAILER AND INFORM HIM THAT THE MATERIAL WOULD HAVE TO BE RETURNED TO EASTERN AIRLINES.  MR. MABRY THEN CONTACTED EASTERN AIRLINES AND NOTIFIED MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM THAT IF SAFELY POSSIBLE TO BRING THE LOAD BACK TO THE EASTERN AIRLINES. MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. WAS CONTACTED BY MR. MATIVI AT 12:35 PM. AND INFORMED PERSONNEL THAT THE TRAILER WAS STILL INCREASING IN TEMPERATURE, SO THAT YOU COULDN'T GET YOUR HAND CLOSER THAN FOUR (4) OF FIVE (5) INCHES FROM IT'S SURFACE.  MR. MATIVI ALSO REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A PRESSURE INCREASE IN THE TANK. MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. THEN CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURER OF THE VACUUM MOTOR FOR GUIDANCE AS TO WHETHER THE PUMP COULD BE USED TO VENT PRESSURE AND STILL CONTAIN ANY LIQUIDS AND CONDENSED VAPORS FROM ESCAPING INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. WAS ALSO CONTACTED BY MR. MABRY AND INFORMED THAT THERE WAS A PRESSURE BUILDUP IN THE TRAILER AFTER MR. MABRY ADVISED THAT EASTERN WOULD REACCEPT THE LOAD. WHEN MR. MATIVI RECONTACTED MEROLA ENTERPRISES, INC. HE WAS MADE AWARE OF THE VACUUM PUMP MANUFACTURERS INSTRUCTIONS AND DIRECTED TO VENT THE TRAILER IF/AS REQUIRED AND TO MOVE THE TRAILER AWAY FROM PEOPLE AND OTHER PEOPLE AND OTHER VEHICLES IF POSSIBLE AND CALL BACK WITHIN 10 MINUTES. MR. MATIVI CONTACTED MEROLA AT 1:35 AND REPORTED THAT THE PRESSU
LIDS POPPED OFF IN TRANSIT.  INK SEGREGATED FROM OTHER FREIGHT.  HELD IN HM HOLDING AREA FOR DISPOSITION.  NO DECONTAMINATION INVOLVED.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON HIGHWAY US93A, APPROXIMATELY 28.5 MILES SOUTHWEST OF WENDOVER.  DRIVER BECAME INATTENTIVE AND DRIFTED TO THE SOUTH ROADWAY UNPAVED SHOULDER. THE DRIVER THEN BECAME ATTENTIVE AND OVER CORRECTED TO THE LEFT CAUSING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TO OVER TURN TO THE RIGHT.  AS THE ROLL-OFF BINS IMPACTED THE GROUND, DAMAGE TO THE RIGHT FRONT AREA OCCURED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED.  WITHIN 24 HOURS THE HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT.  THE WASTE WAS SHIPPED TO US POLLUTION CONTROL, INC.  GRASSY MOUNTAIN FACILITY. SAMPLES WERE TAKEN IN THE SPILL AREA AFTER THE CLEAN-UP TO CERTIFY WAS ACTUALLY CLEAN.  SEE THE ATTACHED SHEET FOR THE LAB ANALYSIS.  SEVERAL STEPS WERE TAKEN TO PREVENT OR TO MINIMIZE THE EFFECTS OF AN ACCIDENT RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  1) A TRAINING PROGRAM WAS ESABLISHED TO ACQUAINT DRIVERS WITH THE RISKS OF INATTENTIVENESS AND FATIGUE AND METHODS TO AVOID THE SAME.  2) AN IMPROVED METHOD OF ATTACHING THE ROLL-OFF BINS TO THE TRUCK WAS ENGINEERED AND INSTIGATED. 3) A STUDY IS PRESENTLY UNDERWAY TO IMPROVE THE DESIGN OF THE ROLL-OFF BINS TO MINIMIZE THE POSSIBILITY OF MATERIAL RELEASE

DRIVER ARRIVED AND TOLD CUSTOMER HE WAS DELIVERING 1180 GALS SULFURIC ACID 66. HE WAS DIRECTED TO THEIR TANK AND WAITED FOR PERSON TO SIGN THAT THE HOOK UP WAS CORRECT AND APPROVED. HE AGAIN TOLD THE CUSTOMER HOW MUCH MATERIAL HE HAD. HE WAS TOLD THAT THERE WAS PLENTY OF ROOM AND STARTED PUMPING INTO THEIR STORAGE TANK. WHILE OBSERVING THE UNLOADING OUR DRIVER SAW THE ACID START TO COMER OVER THE TOP OF THEIR TANK, HE THEN IMMEDIATELY SHUTDOWN APPROX 35 GALS WAS SPILLED INTO THEIR BERM AND APPROX 2 GALS OUTSIDE THE BERM. THIS INFO WAS ALSO CONFIRMED WITH MARCEL AT ANSONIA COPPER AT APPROX 1:30PM. LJ&M LAPLACE NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER 1-800-424-8802, REPORT #103188. PER CRAIG SCHATZLIEN, OF ANSONIA COPPER (1-200-732-6645) THEY NOTIFIED THE CT DEP AND CALLED IN CLEAN HARBOUR TO HANDLE THE SPILL.

ON FRIDAY, 01/03/92 AT 0200 CLEAN VENTURE, INC.'S DRIVER PAUL DERISI HAD PULLED INTO A TRUCK STOP IN DRUMS, PA AT EXIT 39 ON I-80, A ROUTINE STOP TO GET COFFEE AND FOOD, ETC. WHEN FINISHED, HE RETURNED TO HIS TRUCK AND PROCEEDED TO DO A SPOT CHECK OF THE TIRES, LIGHTS, ETC. WHEN HE WALKED AROUND BACK OF TRAILER HE NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BACK. AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION, HE DISCOVERED THAT A 55 GAL DRUM IN THE ERY BACK OF THE TRAILER WAS THE LEAKER. HE PROCEEDED TO STOP THE LEAK BY TURNING THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE. THE TRUCK WAS EQUIPPED WITH A SPILL KIT AND DRIVER, PAUL DERISI, HAS BEEN 40HR SARA/OSHA TRAINED AND DOT TRAINED FOR THE SAFE TRANSPORT OF HAZMAT. HE APPLIED SPEEDY DRY AND ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. ONCE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, HE CALLED THE CLEAN VENTURE, INC. SUPV ON CALL CHARLIE LAKATOS. AN EMERG RESPONSE CREW FROM CLEAN VENTURE RESPONDED WITHIN 3HRS WITH MANPOWER AND EQUIPMENT TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. WE NOTIFIED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES OF THE SITUATION. LUZERNE COUNTY HAZMAT AND FIREMEN WERE ON THE SITE TO ASSIST US. AT 8:00AM THE PA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES WAS CALLED AT 1-717-787-7381 BY BETTY SEAMAN, THE TRANSPORTATION CLERK IN THE PERTH AMBOY OFFICE. THE PERSON WHOM TO SPEAK WITH WAS NOT INT THE OFFICE YET. SHE LEFT THE COMPANY NAME, HER NAME & PHONE NUMBER AND A BRIEF DESCRIPTION OF THE SPILL. AT 8:25AM STAN LEHMAN FROM THE PA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES RETURNED HER CALL. SHE EXPLAINED THE SITUATION. HE HAD ASKED WHAT OUR PROCEDURES WERE GOING TO BE TO CLEAN SPILL. HER RESPONSE WAS THE CREW WOULD OVERPACK THE DRUMS AND CLEAN SPILL MATERIAL INTO ANOTHER DRUM AND DISPOSE OF THE SPILL MATERIAL PROPERLY. HE TOLD HER THAT WE SEEM TO HAVE EVERYTHING UNDER CONTROL AND IF ANY PROBLEMS SHOULD ARISE TO CONTACT HIM AT 1-717-826-2553. WHILE CLEANING THE SPILL IN THE TRAILER WE FOUND ANOTHER DRUM OF THE SAME MATERIAL LEAKING. WE PUT CAUTION TAPE AROUND CONTAMINATED AREAS, OVERPACKED THE 2 LEAKING DRUMS, DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND CLEANED THE SPILLED MATERIAL FROM THE ROAD. AFTER COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN UP, A TOTAL OF THREE 55 GAL DRUMS WERE GENERATED BY THE CONTAMINATED SPILL DEBRIS. THE DRUMS WERE PUT BACK ON THE TRAILER AND SHIPPED BACK TO CYCLE CHEM FOR DISPOSAL UNDER MANIFEST #MI2430419.

WHEN WORKING TRAILER 23-7016, KEN FRANKS (DOCKMAN) NOTICED SOME LEAKAGE FROM THIS DRUM.  WHEN HE MOVED IT, HE NOTICED NO DAMAGE TO THE DRUM, BUT IT WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY FROM THE BOTTOM RIM. I INVESTIGATED AND HAD HIM PUT THE DRUM IN A RECOVERY DRUM. THE LOSS WAS MINIMAL. DELIVERY WAS ATTEMPTED. THIS APPEARED TO BE A PROBLEM WITH THE DRUM...WE NOTICED NO PUNCTURES, HOLES OR SCRAPES ON THE DRUM, JUST THE SEAL ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM THAT WAS NOT TIGHT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE RAN OFF PAVEMENT ONTO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND BECAUSE OF HEAVY RAIN FALLING AND SOFT GROUND, THE VEHICLE ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE, CAUSING A PRODUCT SPILL.  SEVERAL LOCAL FIRE COMPANIES AND THEIR HAZMAT TEAMS RESPONDED AS DID THE SHIPPER'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT AND CARRIER PERSONNEL.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, COAST GUARD, SOUTH CAROLINA DHEC AND OTHER AGENCIES WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED.  SC STATE PATROL CONTROLLED THE HIGHWAY TRAFFIC.  CARRIER'S EMERGENCY RSPONDERS, OHM, CLEANED UP THE SITE UNDER THE DIRECTION OF REGULATORS AFTER THE TRAILER WAS OFF-LOADED AND RIGHTED.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS STARTED IN ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS AT AN APPROVED STAGING AREA AND AFTER APPROVAL BY SC DHEC AND ULTIMATELY DISPOSED OF AT: SANDY PINES LANDFILL, RT 1 BOX 870, DORCHESTER, SC  29437. THIS ACCIDENT WAS ASSIGNED NRC #104-125.

column168: ON 01/15/92, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) H. W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. MARK CONSTANZIO THAT ICRZ 631003 HAD HAZARDOUS WASTE SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND AT BURMESTER YARD.  SSA/HM RODABOUGH RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT BOTH REAR DOORS OF ICRZ 631003 WERE BROKE OPEN AND FOUR DRUMS OF WASTE WERE ON THE GROUND AND AN ADDITIONAL 4 DRUMS STILL IN THE CONTAINER BUT POSITIONED ON THE EDGE OF THE TRAILER.  ONE OF THE DRUMS ON THE GROUND HAD A PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM AND HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKING PRODUCT.  SSA/HM RODABOUGH NOTICED PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER.  LEAKING DRUM WAS PLUGGED AND VISQUENE LAID DOWN TO CATCH LEAKAGE FROM THE TRAILER.  DRUMS WERE LOADED AND REARRANGED.  CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUM AND ALL DRUMS WERE BANDED TOGETHER. TRAILER WAS THEN SECURED FOR MOVEMENT.  AL WILLIAMS, WALT BLAZARD AND RON PORTER OF USPCI WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.

MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, JIM OSBURN OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID DRIPPING DOWN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR NATX 261 FROM THE AREA OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  MANAGER OSBURN BROKE THE CABLE SEAL AND INSPECTED THE HOUSING AREA.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE SAMPLE LINE VALVE.  MANAGER OSBURN WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE VALVE ONE QUARTER TURN WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  FURTHER INSPECTION ALSO DETERMINED THAT PLUG FOR THE VALVE WAS LOOSE.  PLUG WAS TIGHTENED AND PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS SECURED. MANAGER OSBURN NOTIFIED SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON AND BRIEFED HIM ON THE INCIDENT AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS. SSA/HM HILL'S INSPECTED DETERMINED A LOOSE OPERATING ROD AND NO PACKING IN THE PACKING GLAND. UPON DISCOVERY OF LEAKING CONTAINER THE DRIVER SALESMAN CALLED THE TERMINAL TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  DRIVER SALESMAN WAS ADVISED BY THE CITY DISPATCHER TO SURVEY THE AREA AND CLEAR SCENE OF ANY INDIVIDUALS.  THE AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE REPORTED TO CITY DISPATCHER.  CITY DISPATCHER CHECKED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE FOR POTENTIAL HAZARDS.  ANOTHER DRIVER SALESMAN RETURNED THE PAIL AND THE ABSORBENT CLEAN-UP MATERIAL FROM THE LEAKAGE TO THE TERMINAL IN PLASTIC WRAPPING.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED CONTAINER.  MR. DON BROWN OF SHIPPER ADVISED TO RETURN THE PAIL AND THE ABSORBENT CONTENTS TO THE SHIPPER AS SOON AS POSSIBLE IN RECOVERY CONTAINER.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: THE SHIPMENT ORIGINATED AT LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TES), INC IN LA PORTE, TEXAS AND WAS DESTINED TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF BARTOW, INC. ON JANUARY 14, 1992.  SEVEN DRUMS WERE REJECTED AT THIS DESTINATION.  AT THE GENERATOR'S INSTRUCTION, THE SEVEN DRUMS WERE DESIGNATED TO BE SHIPPED TO AN ALTERNATE DISPOSAL FACILITY:  LAIDLAW ENVIRONMETNAL SERVICES (TS), INC. LOCATED AT 5303 126TH AVE NORTH IN CLEARWATER, FLORIDA 34620.  THE DRUMS INVOLVED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENT APPEARED ON MANIFEST DOCUMENT NUMBER 22956. ON JANUARY 22, 1992, THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ON THE REAR OF A TRAILER DESTINED FOR LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. IN CLEARWATER, FLORIDA.  THE DRUMS WERE PACKAGED ON PALLETS.  LOAD BARS WERE USED TO SECURE THE SHIPMENT.  LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. WAS THE MOTOR CARRIER. IN ROUTE, THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO BRAKE ABRUPTLY IN ORDER TO STOP AT A CHANGING TRAFFIC LIGHT.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE SUDDEN STOP CAUSED TO LOAD TO SHIFT.  HE THEN PROCEEDED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION AND PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  UPON INSPECTING THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER RECOGNIZED THAT SOME LIQUIDS WERE LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS.  HE OBTAINED HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, INCLUDING A RESPIRATOR, ENTERED THE TRAILER AND CONTAINED THE SPILLAGE WITH ABSORBENT. FOUR DRUMS HAD FALLED FORWARD, KNOCKING THE LOAD BAR LOOSE.  TWO DRUMS REMAINED INTACT.  HOWEVER, THE BUNG CLOSURE HAD POPPED OUT OF THE OTHER TWO CONTAINERS.  ONE DRUM WAS LESS THAT ONE-THIRD FULL AND THE OTHER WAS TWO-THIRDS FULL AFTER THE DRIVER HAD SECURED BOTH DRUMS. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED FROM LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (TS), INC. IN CLEARWATER, FLORIDA IN ORDER TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE.  ALL LIQUIDS WERE ABSORBED AND COLLECTED.  THE CREW DECONTAMINATED APPROXIMATELY 120 FEET OF THE CURB, USING A WATER AND ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL SOLUTION.  THE DECONTAMINATION SOLUTION WAS ABSORBED AND COLLECTED.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WILL BE DISPOSED AT LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES(TS), INC. IN CLEARWATER, FLORIDA.  DISPOSAL WILL BE MADE IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THE HILLSBOROUGH COUNTY, FLORIDA, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SITE AS CLEANUP OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED.  THEY WERE PLEASED WITH THE CLEANUP EFFORT.  ADDITIONAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THEY INCLUDE: A) NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (WASHINGTON, DC): PETTY OFFICER BESHOAR WAS NOTIFIED.  THE RELATED REPORT NUMBER IS 104053. B) FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATION (TALLAHASSEE, FLORIDA): DOUG WHITE WAS NOTIFIED. C) FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL REGULATION, SOUTHWEST DISTRICT OFFICE (TAMPA, FLORIDA); BETH KNASUSS WAS NOTIFIED. D) FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (TALLAHASSEE, FLORIDA); AUDRY TAYLOR WAS NOTIFIED. E) HILLSBOROUGH COUNTY, FLORIDA, EMERGENCY PLANNING DEPARTMENT (TAMPA, FLORIDA); JIM LOUTH WAS NOTIFIED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON JANUARY 18, 1992 AT 11:30 PM OUR WAKE UP DRIVER, JAY LAWSON, WAS UNLOADING UNLEADED GASOLINE AT AKARD'S SELF-SERVICE STATION #61 AT 505 N JACKSON STREET, FRANKFORT, INDIANA.  DRIVER JAY LAWSON FAILED TO BE ALERT AND WATCHFUL WHILE UNLOADING UNLEADED GASOLINE.  DRIVER JAY LAWSON HAD MADE AN IMPROPER CONNECTION TO THE FILL PIPE WHICH RESULTED IN A SMALL SPILL OF 674 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE.  DRIVER JAY LAWSON CONTACTED THE FRANKFORT FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALSO AT THIS TIME ALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS WERE CONTACTED.  FRANKFORT POLICE DEPARTMENT, FRANKFORT (CLINTON COUNTY) EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT TEAMS, INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA.  THE AREA AFFECTED BY THIS SPILL WAS 100' BY 300' FROM SAID STATION.  THE TOTAL SPILL HAS BEEN COMPLETELY CONTAINED AND CLEAN UP IS COMPLETE.  THERE WAS NO FISH KILL OR CONTAMINATED SOIL.  DRIVER JAY LAWSON HAS BEEN DISCHARGED FOR HIS NEGLECT AND NOT COMPLYING WITH COMPANY WORK RULES.

column168: I, BENJAMIN W. TAYLOR, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORDINATOR, ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177, WHILE PERFORMING ANY NORMAL DUTIES IN THE OFFICE AND STANDING BY FOR ANY CALLS CONCERNING HAZARDOUS OR NON-HAZARDOUS SPILLS DRUING OUR DAYTIME SORT OPERATION, RECEIVED A CALL OVER THE RADIO FROM DAY SORT LEAD CONNIE ROE THAT SHE HAD A PACKAGE AT DOOR B-27 (B-BLDG) LEAKING A LIQUID AND THAT SHE HAD AN ODOR OF BLEACH.  SHE ALSO REPORTED THAT SHE HAD ONE (1) EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT, WHO SHE INSTRUCTED TO GO WASH HER HANDS WITH WARM WATER AND LIQUID SOAP (STANDARD PROCEDURE). UPON ARIVAL, I AND SPILL SPECIALIST ADDIE CAMPTON MET WITH DAY SORT LEAD CONNIE ROE AND THE EMPLOYEE (LORI CONGER) WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LEAKING PACKAGE.  AT THIS TIME, I WAS ADVISED BY THE EMPLOYEE THAT THE JERSEY GLOVES SHE WAS WEARING AT THE TIME WERE "BLEACHED" WHITE.  I AND SPILL SPECIALIST ADDIE CAMPTON DONNED DOUBLE PROTECTIVE GLOVES, GLASSES AND MASK (STANDARD PROCEDURE) AND BEGAN EXAMINING THE OUTERMOST PART OF THE PACKAGE, VISUALLY LOOKING FOR ANY MARKINGS, LABELS OR PACKING SLIPS THAT WOULD GIVE A DESCRIPTION OR INDICATION OF WHAT THE INNER CONTENTS MAY BE.  THE ONLY INDICATION THAT THE INNER CONTENTS MAY BE A HOUSEHOLD PRODUCT WAS THE ODOR OF BLEACH AND THE DECOLORATION OF THE EMPLOYEE'S JERSEY GLOVES.  OTHER INDICATORS WAS THE FACT THAT THE BOX WAS A U-HAUL FIBREBOARD BOX USED IN MOVING AND STORAGE AND ALSO THE FACT THAT THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE OF THE SAME COMPANY AND THE PERSON SHIPPING THE PACKAGE WAS ALSO THE SAME PERSON TO RECEIVE IT IN THE CITY TO WHICH IT WAS DESTINED.
